.SHORT TERM...
Issued at 1245 AM PDT Thu Jul 23 2026
(Today and tonight)

Patchy coastal low clouds are trying to redevelop early this
morning. Higher dewpoint air lingers, however areal low cloud
coverage will depend on the total amount of nocturnal radiative
cooling (improved since it`s drier aloft) and near surface cool
air advection through morning. Putting the brakes on low cloud
development so far is the recent uptick in sea surface temperatures
with the loss of cold water upwelling due to the recent northward
moving remnant low center passing by to our west. The buoys show
sea surface temps in the upper 50s to lower 60s, about 3F to 8F
above July normals. However, northwest winds (and upwelling) will
resume in our coastal waters today and tonight.

High pressure aloft will continue to bring stable weather. Daytime
highs today will be in the 60s/70s coastside to the 70s/80 bayside
and 80s/90s inland including 90s/100 over the southern interior.
Lows in the 50s to lower 60s tonight.

