.AVIATION...
(12Z TAFS)
Issued at 425 AM PDT Thu Jul 23 2026

The marine layer is 1400 feet deep, and is battling some dry air.
As such the stratus coverage is ragged and flight conditions are
likely to change for better or worse as this mixing continues
through the early morning hours. The confidence is very low with
this set of TAFs, even in the short term. The clouds will retreat
back to the coast late this morning with VFR conditions and
moderate onshore winds through the afternoon.

Vicinity of SFO...Very tricky forecast here. Boundary layer
averaged winds are from the NW, and with the compressing marine
layer the terminal is getting some IFR stratus from the west, MVFR
stratus from the east, and clear skies to the south. Since the
terminal is at the intersection, the flight condition is liable to
change quickly through the morning hours. Don`t put too much trust
in my TAF this morning. The clouds will clear in the late morning
with strong onshore winds expected from late morning through the
evening.

SFO Bridge Approach...Currently clear and very slowly filling with
IFR ceilings from the north.

Monterey Bay Terminals...MRY actually reported fog for a brief
period this morning, but that has lifted to a LIFR stratus deck.
The marine layer is very ragged across the Monterey Bay region,
but it`s unlikely that MRY or SNS clear before the late morning
hours.

